<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-24T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-24T14:00:00-05:00" n="579" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d579">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.516/693: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-24T14:00:00-05:00">October 24, 1940—2
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>418. Reference your 1027, October 22, 5 p.m. The Department concurs
                                in your suggested course of action. It is assumed, of course, that
                                in your communication to the Minister for Foreign Affairs you will
                                not use the term “Chinese Government at Nanking”.<note n="27" xml:id="d579fn27">In telegram No. 1058, October 26, 7 p.m., the
                                    Ambassador in Japan reported that representations were made to
                                    the Japanese Foreign Minister on that date
                                (893.516/698).</note></p>
                            <p>Sent to Tokyo via Shanghai. Repeated to Peiping, Nanking.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>